title: 787 Racing 3 and 6 Hour Mountain Bike Race
2017 Miles of DisComfort Mtn Bike Marathon
Tommy Ketterhagen Memorial Ride
description:
We are both saddened and outraged to learn of the tragic death of our friend and teammate, 19-year-old Tommy Ketterhagen. The entire Ketterhagen family has been a part of 787 Racing since the team's formation, and Tommy has been a fixture at rides and races for a number of years. Even off the bike, we were blessed with Tommy's happy-go-lucky attitude, his love for his friends and family, and the honesty and sincerity of his character. Our collective hearts go out to his parents, his brothers and sisters, and all others who were fortunate to know him.
We would be remiss if we did not repeat the call to action being shared due to the circumstances surrounding Tommy's death. Tommy was allegedly killed by a hit-and-run driver sometime after 5PM on the evening of Monday, January 23, 2017 in east Georgetown, TX. Firstly, if you saw Tommy last night, or otherwise have any relevant information, please contact Detective Kirby Shoemake of the Georgetown Police Department at 512-930-8491. Moreover, it is infuriating to have to repeat the continued plea for increased awareness and respect of cyclists (and other vulnerable road users) in the wake of yet another inhumane death. This has to stop.
course: The ride is to celebrate the life of Tommy Ketterhagen.  It will start at East View High School, 4490 E University Ave, Georgetown, Texas 78626.
directions: East View High School, 4490 E University Ave, Georgetown, Texas 78626

description:
The 34th annual Matrix Challenge will once again be contested on the tree lined streets of the Meadows Foundations Wilson Historic District and along historic Swiss Avenue. The challenging eight-turn race will test racers handling skills and strength while providing spectators a unique and up-close view of the racing action.

The race weekend will follow two separate race schedules in order to accommodate as many unique category race starts as possible. The race course reversal returns this year for Sundays events (counter-clockwise). Finally, the weekends total cash purse and primes will exceed $8K. The Matrix Cycle Club looks forward to seeing you on Swiss Avenue the second weekend of April for Dallas most exciting criterium racing!
course:
The famed Swiss Avenue race venue is located immediately northeast of the Dallas Central Business District and within the Wilson Historic District at the footsteps of Dallas Baylor Medical Center. Please review the online Google Map highlighting parking, registration, race staging, restrooms and street closures. Course will be run clockwise Saturday and counter-clockwise Sunday.

Swiss Ave. @ Liberty St. -- Dallas, TX -- 75204

http://bit.ly/matrixchallenge
registration: Online registration* is available through USA Cycling closing Wed., April 5th at midnight CST (* subject to convenience fees). Discounted, early registration for adult categories ends Fri., March 31st at midnight CST. Regular registration fees for adult categories will be in effect Sat. April 1st. On-site, race-day registration opens at 6:45 AM and will incur a one-time $5 late fee for all categories based on the regular registration fee (registration closes 20 min prior to an events start time). Additional USAC race registrations per day are $20 each.
notes:
This years race will utilize the race|result ActivePro RF-ID transponder for lap timing/scoring (the same system utilized for NTXCX events and King Racing Group's Thursday night Fair Park Crit series). Each competitor is required to use a transponder for scoring purposes or they will not be included in their event's tabulated results. You may purchase your own transponder ($67) or rent one ($5/day). If you own a transponder, please enter it's serial number in the field labeled "other" on the registration form.

If you rent a transponder you must stop after your finish and return your transponder at our post-event collection point (you will be notified on the start line of the location). Please do not leave the race course until you have returned your rental transponder.

Red Bull Last Stand is a criterium that races around the iconic Alamo Plaza in San Antonio, TX with a twist, each lap the last rider is eliminated until only the last rider remains.

Qualifying:

A 15-minute timed open group session of approximately 50 riders with the fastest transponder time used to qualify and seed the top 50 riders for the Mens Finals and top 30 riders for the Womens Finals

Finals:
	Mens finals will be 50 laps with the last rider across the finish line being removed after every lap until one last rider remains.
	Womens finals will be 30 laps with the last rider across the finish line being removed after every lap until one last rider remains.
	There will be no free laps for mishaps, crashes, or mechanicalsthe last rider across the line will be eliminated, period.
	There will be no benefit for lapping the field, if a rider laps the field they will be on the same lap of the field.
course:

title: Waco Wild West 100
description: Family friendly tour ride, non competitive event on rural roads.
course:
All routes are supported with rest stops and police at busy crossings.
Due to construction on the China Spring Highway we have changed the routes to bypass the section under construction. Please take note of the route changes.
10 Mile Route
This is a fun ride for the family. Start at the starting line with all the riders but ride through Wacos beautiful Cameron Park and then back to downtown Waco on the paved bike path along Martin Luther King Drive. Tour a little bit of downtown before you head to the finish line. There are several rest stops to make it a fun ride for all.
27 Mile Route
The 27 mile route is also fun for families and recreational riders. This route is quite flat and passes by the Lake Waco Dam and the peaceful surrounding countryside.
Head out Martin Luther King toward the Waco Airport. Loop around on Flat Rock and Yankie before you head back. Ride through Cameron Park as you head toward the finish line.
52 Mile Route
The 52 mile route is relatively flat with a few challenging hills thrown in to keep you from getting bored!
Our most popular route takes you all around the city of Waco and surrounding areas. The first few miles are the same as the 27 mile route. Then you head toward China Spring on back roads then head back around to Speegleville, then up the dreaded Hwy 84 hill. Then head towards Hewitt, out to Robinson and back to Waco on University Parks. Get a glimpse of the new Baylor Stadium as you ride through the Baylor campus and then on to the finish line.
68 Mile route
The 68 mile route follows more of the 100 mile route and takes in some great rural roads.
You will head to Crawford after the 3rd rest stop. Enjoy the scenery and then end up back with the 52 mile route in Speegleville.
102 Mile Route
This route covers picturesque countryside on rural roads in McLennan and Bosque counties. Although relatively flat, there are some challenging hills to keep your heart pumping.
The 102 mile route takes you from Crawford, out to Oglesby, through some private lands and beautiful countryside. A few little hills to keep it interesting. You will ride very close to Mother Neff State Park and then head back toward McGregor. You might hear some rumbling from rocket engines tests at SpaceX. Wind your way through more back roads till you join the 52 and 68 mile routes going up the Hwy 84 hill. Go through Hewitt, Robinson and then head back to downtown Waco where you can fill your helmet with candy.
This year our 102 mile ride will have two cut off points.
1. The first cut off point will be at the 30 mile Crawford rest stop. Riders arriving after 10:30 am will be required to ride the 68 mile route.
2. The second cut off point for the 102 mile ride will be at the Oglesby rest stop. Oglesby is 40.5 miles into our ride. Riders arriving after 11:30 am will be required to continue down FM1996 to FM107 and merge with the existing 102 mile route. This cut off will take 12 miles off of the 102 mile route

title: Iceman's Challenge Ultra Gravel Race and Adventure Pursuit
description:
The 4th Annual Iceman's Challenge Gravel Road Race and Adventure Pursuit is a fun, laid back gravel adventure event held at the historic Talbert Ranch in China Spring, Texas. The Iceman's Challenge is a race and adventure ride organized to give gravel riders an opportunity to ride of some of the remote and most beautiful country roads in McLennan and Bosque Counties.  This year we offer an 86 Mile Ultra Gravel Road Race and  Adventure Pursuit Ride and courses of 86, 68, 54, and 36 miles.  The event takes place on Saturday, December 2, 2017, near Waco, Texas, with all courses located in McLennan and Bosque Counties.  The Iceman's Challenge offers routes along beautiful gravel roads, some shaded by trees and on sunlit country roads taking you through farm and ranch lands meandering by rivers and crossing creeks, and streams.  The four courses offered will feature roads with varying surface conditions from compacted gravel, small cinder-like sand, smooth dirt, rocky to smooth water crossings, rutted wash outs, chip seal and smooth asphalt pavement.  For 2017, the 86 mile and 68 mile courses will offer a new section called the Angel's Lair featuring four challenging climbs and descents with some spectacular views from the highest elevations in Bosque County.   Course routes average between 90-75% gravel roads with 20-25% paved roads.  


As in our past events, we strive to offer a high quality event and to give back to our local community which supports the Iceman's Challenge Gravel Pursuit and welcomes event participants.  Each year we select a deserving charity or organization to donate our net proceeds on behalf of all our event participants, sponsors, and volunteers. The 4th Annual Icemans Challenge Gravel Race and Pursuit is very pleased to announce The Arc of McLennan County as our 2017 Community Charity Campaign donation recipient.  The mission of the Arc of McLennan County is to expand opportunities, care, and support for persons and families impacted by intellectual and developmental disabilities.  For specific information or to make a direct donation to The Arcs programs, please visit www.wacoarc.org


For event details and specific information regarding event schedule, maps, locations, FAQs, event rules, and contact information please go to our officlal website at http://www.icemanschallenge.com.  For important event updates and current information please follow us on our Facebook Page at  https://www.facebook.com/Icemans-Challenge-Road-to-Hell-Gravel-Advenuture-Ride-1655202051402244/

Upon leaving the paved section of Talbert Ranch road you will enter the ranch through it's main entrance gate.  Please lower your speed limit to 15 miles per hour as you travel to the ranch.  Do not leave designated roadways for any reason.  There will be loose cattle and the family pet dogs which will be along the gravel road leading up to the Talbert Ranch HQ home and barn facilities.  We do not want to injure their livestock or pets in any way.
